        <h1><i class="fas fa-bolt"></i> Temporal Force</h1>
        <p>
            The <strong>Temporal Force</strong> is a fundamental concept within the Unified Universe Theory. It is a force 
            that drives the expansion of the universe along the time dimension, similar to how gravity influences objects 
            within the spatial dimensions. However, unlike gravity, the Temporal Force is not directly observable. We 
            experience it as the passage of time.
        </p>
        <p>
            Mathematically, the Temporal Force is expressed as:
        </p>
        <div class="math-equation">
            <span>F<sub>t</sub> = ρ / c</span>
        </div>
        <p>
            Here, <strong>F<sub>t</sub></strong> represents the Temporal Force, <strong>ρ</strong> is the local spacetime density, 
            and <strong>c</strong> is the speed of light. This equation implies that the Temporal Force is directly proportional 
            to the density of spacetime and inversely proportional to the speed of light. As the density of spacetime 
            increases, so does the Temporal Force, which influences the rate at which time flows.
        </p>

        <!-- Simplified Explanation -->
        <h2><i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> Simplified Explanation</h2>
        <p>
            Imagine the universe is a giant river. The flow of the river represents the passage of time. Just like how the current of a river can push objects along its path, the Temporal Force pushes everything in the universe forward through time. The stronger the current, the faster things move. If the river's current slows down, everything in it moves slower—just like how time seems to slow down in places with a stronger Temporal Force.
        </p>
        
